<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-20T19:50:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-20T19:50:00-05:00" n="397" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d397">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/1019: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief of the United States Asiatic
                                Fleet</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Yarnell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chief of Naval
                                Operations</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi></persName>)<note n="54" xml:id="d397fn54">Copy
                                transmitted to the Department by the Navy Department.</note></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-21T08:50:00+08:00">September 21, 1937—8:50
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received September 21—7 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>0021. Orders have been given Comyangpat<note n="55" xml:id="d397fn55">Commander, U. S. Yangtze Patrol (Marquart).</note> to keep a
                            gunboat at Nanking as long as there are any United States nationals
                            there who may require assistance or protection.</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>